 Verenigd Koninkrijk","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1315–1407":"1315–1407","1312–Male":"1312–Deceased","1320–Female":"1320–Deceased","1350–1407":"1350–1407","1285–Male":"1285–Deceased","1290–Female":"1290–Deceased","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","1320":"1320","1285":"1285","1350":"1350","1407":"1407","1290":"1290","Dennington, Suffolk, England":"Dennington, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Dennington, Suffolk, England, UK":"Dennington, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Phelp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Scottish, English: variant of   Philp  ;  see  Philip   and  compare  Phalp  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Phalp","meanings":["Scottish, English:  see  Philip  ."]},{"name":"Philip","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Varughese, Mathai, Babu, Reji, Anil, Binu, Neena, Prema, Raju, Reena, Susheela, Aleykutty.","Scottish, English, German, Dutch, and Jewish: from the Greek personal name <i>Philippos</i> (from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’). In the New Testament this name is borne by one of the apostles; it was also borne by various other early Christian saints. It owes part of its popularity to the medieval romances about Alexander the Great, whose father was Philip of Macedon. As a Jewish name, it represents a borrowing of the personal name from Christians. As a Highland Scottish surname, it represents an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhilib</b> ‘son of Philip’. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Spanish   Felipe  , Catalan <b>Felip</b>, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovenian or Croatian   Filip  , Albanian   Filipi  , and their derivatives (see examples at   Philips  ). The name <i>Philip</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Philipose   and   Pothen  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Phillip  .","French (southern) and Breton (Finistère): variant of   Philippe  ."]},{"name":"Philp","meanings":["Scottish and English (Cornwall): shortened form of   Philip  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Phelp was born in 1315, in Dennington, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard Phelp, was 31 and his mother, Isabella, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Phelp. He died in 1407, in his hometown, at the age of 92, and was buried in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1315–1407":"1315–1407","1312–Male":"1312–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1350–1407":"1350–1407","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","1320":"1320","1285":"1285","1350":"1350","1407":"1407","1290":"1290","Dennington, Suffolk, England":"Dennington, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dennington, Suffolk, England, UK":"Dennington, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1315–1407":"1315–1407","1312–Male":"1312